column168: Description Of Events

DRIVER STOPPED AT THE PILOT TRUCK STOP ON I-10, BAYTOWN, TX FOR A SNACK.  HE DID A WALK AROUND OF HIS UNIT AND NOTICED A COUPLE OF DROPS FROM THE VALVE FLANGE ON THE REAR BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER AND CALLED IT IN TO OUR CENTRAL DISPATCH.  A MECHANIC WAS SENT TO THE TRUCK STOP AND HE FOUND A COUPLE LOOSE BOLTS, WHICH HE TIGHTENED.  THE AREA STILL APPEARED TO BE SEEPING SLIGHTLY, SO A RESPONSE WAS DONE BY THE COMPANY AND THE SHIPPER.  A BUCKET HAD BEEN SET UNDER THE LEAK WHEN DISCOVERED BY THE DRIVER, HOWEVER WHAT LITTLE LEAKED EVAPORATED BEFORE HITTING THE BUCKET.  IT WAS DECIDED BY THE COMPANY AND SHIPPER THAT WE WOULD TRANSFER THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TRAILER, WHICH WAS DONE AT OUR BAYTOWN TERMINAL.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE VALVE VACUUM TESTED BY THE SHIPPER PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO LEAKS WERE DISCOVERED.  THE BOLTS APPARENTLY LOOSENED IN TRANSIT.

column168: CREWS REPORTED FOUL ODOR NEAR TANK CAR GATX 17243, A RESIDUE SHIPMENT OF CORROSIVE LIQUIDS NOS (CONTAINING SODIUM SULFIDE AND SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTIONS).  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE PACKING GLAND ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED FROM ITS LOOSENED POSITION TO STOP THE LEAK.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

SWITCH CREW REPORTED UTLX 99349, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA LOAD, TO BE LEAKING.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED CAR AND FOUND THAT THE INTEGRITY OF THE THERMOMETER WELL PIPE HAD BEEN COMPROMISED INSIDE THE TANK.  PRODUCT ESCAPED DUE TO DETERIORATED SEAL IN THE CAP OF THE PIPE.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR TRUCKS TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT TO DESTINATION, AS WELL AS A SCRUBBER TANK TRUCK TO DEPLETE THE REMAINING PRESSURE.  THE CAR WAS THEN ROUTED TO A REPAIR FACILITY.

CREWS ADVISED OF FOUL ODOR IN THE VICINITY OF TANK CAR GATX 45821, A RESIDUE OF SODIUM SULFIDE/SODIUM HYDROXIDE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED CAR AND FOUND THREE DEFECTS: (A) MANWAY GASKET DETERIORATED AND TORN (B) ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE (C) VAPOR VALVE LOOSE.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND ALL BOLTS FULLY TIGHTENED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO HOME SHOP FOR REPLACEMENT OF VAPOR VALVE.

YARD CREWS REPORTED SMELL OF AMMONIA IN VICINTY OF TANK CAR UTLX 99200, A RESIDUE SHIPMENT.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND VAPOR LEAKING FROM VALVE STEM ON THE LIQUID LINE VALVE.  THE HANDLE NUT WAS FULLY TIGHTENED TO STOP THE RELEASE. CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: CITIZEN REPORTED SMELL OF GAS IN THE VICINITY OF GATX 40740.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND LPG VAPOR ESCAPING FROM SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  IT APPEARED THAT THE SRV HAD NOT RESEATED AFTER LIFTING.  PRESSURE READING WAS 270 PSI AND 9 NCHES OF VAPOR SPACE WAS NOTED. AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS 100*F, WITH NUMEROUS DAYS IN EXCESS OF 100* PREVIOUSLY.  CAR WAS PROMPTLY SWITCHED TO DESTINATION FOR IMMEDIATE UNLOADING.  ALL INDICATIONS SHOW THAT CAR WAS OVERFILLED FOR CLIMATE AT DESTINATION, ESPECIALLY WHITE STORED UNTIL ORDERED FOR UNLOADING.
WAX REMOVER FOR FABRICS, CRAYON & CANDLE AND ADHESIVE & GOO. REMOVER, ONE BOTTLE TOP WAS NOT TIGHTEN, AND CAUSING IT TO LEAK FROM THE BOTTLE, IT IS NOT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE REQUIRED 3 STOPS.  AFTER UNLOADING 3500 GALLONS AT THE FIRST STOP, THE PRODUCT WAS AIRED OFF, VALVES TURNED OFF, LINES BLOWN OUT AND THE AIR COMPRESSOR ON THE TRUCK WAS TURNED OFF.  THE DRIVER THEN WENT TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO DISCONNECT THE HOSE AND FOUND PRODUCT STILL COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER BUT SLOWLY.  WHEN THE DRIVER MOVED THE HOSE TO INVESTIGATE, PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT ONTO HIS LEG CAUSING A SMALL BURN ON THE UPPER THIGH AND A SPILL OF 15 TO 20 GALLONS ONTO THE GROUND.  ON SITE PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  ONE OR BOTH VALVES FAILED ON THE TRAILER WHICH PREVENTED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM BEING STOPPED.  THE TRAILER HAS BEEN SENT FOR REPAIRS.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN CAUTIONED TO ALWAYS WEAR PROTECTIVE CLOTHING, THE COMPLETE OUTFIT THAT HAS BEEN SUPPLIED, WHEN UNLOADING PRODUCT OF THIS NATURE.
WAREHOUSE TECHNICIAN WAS STAGING WHEN HE BUMPED DRUM ACCIDENTALLY PIERCING THE BOTTOM OF DRUM.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER NORTHBOUND ON FM 1485 NEAR GRANGERLAND, TX. AT ITS INTERSECTION WITH FM 3083 THERE IS A GRADUAL CURVE TO THE LEFT AND BANKED TO THE INSIDE. TO FOLLOW THE CURVE, FM1485 BECOMES FM3083 AND FM1485 MAKES A NEAR 90 DEGREE TURN TO THE RIGHT AT THE TRAFFIC LIGHT CONTROLLED INTERSECTION. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO MAKE THE RIGHT TURN TO FOLLOW FM 1485 AND IN THE PROCESS, ROLLED OVER ON THE UNIT'S LEFT SIDE ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND THEN SLID OFF THE ROADWAY INTO THE DITCH. THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER NEXT TO THE WELD AT THE FRONT HEAD CRACKED WHEN IT HIT THE PAVEMENT. THE CRACK WAS APPROXIMATELY 8 - 10" LONG AND 3/8" TO 1/2" WIDE. THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER FLATTENED WHEN IT HIT THE PAVEMENT, INCLUDING THE HEAD AND THE DISTORTION CREATED PUT A STRAIN ON THE METAL NEXT TO THE WELD AND CRACKED. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE DITCH IN THE AREA OF THE ACCIDENT. THE AREA WAS "FOAMED" TO KEEP THE VAPORS DOWN AND THEN PUMPED INTO TRAILERS. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS CLEANED UP BY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.

AFTER LOADING, WHEN TRUCK MOVED TO DO SLOSH TEST, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A CRACK IN THE NIPPLE BETWEEN THE TOP OF TRAILER AND THE TEE IN THE PIPING FOR THE AIR INLET. THIS WAS A 3/4 INCH DIAMETER NIPPLE. REPAIRS WERE MADE TO TRAILER ON THE SITE BY REPLACING THE CRACKED NIPPLE. SHIPPER PERSONNEL PERFORMED CLEANUP OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO ADDITIONAL PROPERTY DAMAGE.

WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY, A DRUM FELL FROM A SKID CAUSING THE DRUM TO PUNCTURE. A CERTIFIED RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM WERE TRANSFERRED INTO A NEW DRUM BY THE CONSIGNEE AND THE RESPONSE TEAM CLEANED AND NEUTRALIZED THE TRAILER.

A CYLINDER OF CARBON DIOXIDE FELL, BREAKING THE VALVE. THE CYLINDER WAS ALLOWED TO LEAK EMPTY AND THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: DRIVER MISHANDLED THE SHIPMENT CAUSING ONE BOX TO FALL AND BREAK ONE GALSS BOTTLE INSIDE THE BOX WHICH CONTAINED 4 GLASS BOTTLES OF 6.1.  IMMEDIATELY THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY ABSORBANT COMPOUNDS AND WAS STORED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER.  THE DRIVER HAS RECEIVED DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS AND OTHER EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN MADE AWARE OF THE IMPORTANCE OF HANDLING HAZMAT.

WHILE MOVING FREIGHT ON DOCK ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED, RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH 20 MIL. CHEMICAL LINER. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
WHEN DOCKMAN OPENED TRAILER DOOR HE NOTICED A HISSING SOUND AND FOUND ONE CYLINDER OF GAS LEAKING.THE CYLINDER WAS ALLOWED TO VENT EMPTY AND WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: ONE BOX WAS HIT BY A FORKLIFT, DAMAGING ONE JUG. HALF THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT AND EVAPORATED. THE DAMAGED BOX WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER. A DRUM WAS DISCOVERED SEEPING FROM A LOOSE BOLT ON LID. THE BOLT WAS TIGHTENED, THE SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED WITH PH-9 AND THE SHIPMENT FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, FORKLIFT PUNCTURED A DRUM EMPTYING ITS CONTENTS. THE SPILLAGE IMMEDIATELY EVAPORATED AND THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS DECONTAMINATED AND DISPOSED OF PROMPTLY. THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED.
FOUR BOXES WERE FOUND DAMAGED WHEN UNLOADED. ALL PRODUCT WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE OVERPACK WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, ONE CARTON WAS FOUND STAINED. THE CARTON WAS OPENED AND ONE BOTTLE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE CAP. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE BOTTLE AND CARTON WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH PH-9. THE CARTON WAS THEN DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

THE SKID BROKE CAUSING FORKLIFT BLADE TO STRIKE AND PUNCTURE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

AFTER DRIVER RECEIVED THE OKAY TO UNLOAD, HE PRESSURIZED HIS TRAILER AND STARTED TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK TO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK. AFTER ABOUT 45 MINUTES OF UNLOADING, HE HEARD LIQUID RUNNING. HE CHECKED THE OVERFILL VENT LINE ON STORAGE TANK AND NO PRODUCT WAS DISCHARGING.  HE SHUT OFF INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES ON CARGO TANK AND THEN CHECKED STORAGE TANK AGAIN.  SAW PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN SIDES OF TANK.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN DIKED AREA AND NEUTRALIZED BY CONSIGNEE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALS THAT PRODUCT CAME OUT OF DOME LOCATED TOP OF STORAGE TANK.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: EMPLOYEE WAS REMOVING HER LOCK CAP FROM VALVE ON 500 LP TANK TO REMOVE PRODUCT AND SEAT IN VALVE DIDN'T SEAT PROPERLY. LOSING 400 GALLONS OF LP GAS INTO AIR. HIGHLAND RD WAS CLOSED FOR 20 MINUTES FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED ( NO FIRE OR INJURIES).  TOTAL TIME OF INCIDENT 30 MINUTES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: I HOOKED UP HOSES SAME AS ALWAYS WAS INSTRUCTED BY ANOTHER DSI DRIVER.  I TURNED ON VALVE AT END OF HOSE NEXT TO METER AS INSTRUCTED.  STARTED PUMP ON TRUCK, BEFORE I COULD FINISH SETTIN PUMP, DISCHARGE HOSE CAME APART NEXT TO VALVE. AFTER CONTAINING SPILL I FOUND ANOTHER VALVE HAD BEEN CLOSED.  GATE VALVE BEYOUND METER.  THIS VALVE HAS ALWAYS BEEN ON (I WAS TOLD WE ONLY HAD THE ONE VALVE BEFORE METER TO OPEN).  TO CONTAIN AREA I SUCKED UP CONTAINMENT AREA WITH TRUCK PUMP IN TO MY EMPTY COMPARTMENT.  THEN PUMPED THIS COMPARTMENT (16 GALLONS)  REST OF TRAILER.  AT THIS TIME I USED SPILL RAGS AND WRUNG THEM OUT INTO A BUCKET.  I WAS TOLD BY BEN WEAVER (DISPATCHER DSI) TO LEAVE ONE OF MY PUMP HOSES TO TEMPORILY REPLACE BROKEN HOSE.  ALSO NO MORE THAN 3-4 GALLONS SPILLED IN DIRT OUTSIDE OF CONTAINMENT AREA.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER AND OPERATOR HOOKED UP HOSES FROM CARGO TANK TO PUMP AND PUMP TO STORAGE TANK CONNECTION.  WHEN DRIVER STARTED TRACTOR PUMP TO UNLOAD IT IMMEDIATELY STARTED LEAKING BADLY.  THE PUMP WAS SHUT OFF, VALVES CLOSED, AND THE HOSES BLOWN CLEAR.  THE PACKING (GASKET MATERIAL) ON THE PUMP SHAFT WAS APPARENTLY WORN AND PERMITTED LEAKAGE.  PUMP WAS REPAIRED AND UNLOADING COMPLETED ON THE FOLLOWING DAY.  PUMPS ARE TO BE CHECKED FOR LEAKS WHEN THEY ARE CLEANED AND ADJUSTMENTS MADE. THIS SHOULD ELIMINATE THIS FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.

column62: Over-pressurized; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: A CATASTROPHIC LOSS OF AIR PRESSURE TO THE TANK TRAILER'S BRAKES CAUSED THE TRAILER BRAKES TO LOCK UP.  DRIVER MAINTAINED CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE UNTIL PASSENGER SIDE WHEELS FELL OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  TRACTOR AND TRAILER FELL ON TOP OF A GUARDRAIL.  ABOUT 1 PINT OF PRODUCT SLOSHED FROM THE RUPTURE DISK. OTHERWISE, THE TANK TRAILER'S CONTENTS WERE INTACT.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO DISPOSE OF SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FOR APPORXIMATELY 19 HOURS (WESTBOUND LANES, EASTBOUND LANES WERE REOPEND AFTER ABOUT2 HOURS).  SO FAR, NO CAUSE FOR THE LOSS OF AIR PRESSURE TO THE BRAKES HAS BEEN DETERMINED.  TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE INSPECTED BY MARYLAND HIGHWAY PATROL AFTERWARDS.  NO CAUSE DISCOVERED.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: DRIVER PULLED ONTO SHIPPER SCALE AFTER LOADING AND WHEN HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK HE NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OF TRAILER FROM UNDER THE OUTER SKIN.  IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE NITRIC ACID, AND THE TANK WAS TAKEN BACK AND OFF LOADED INTO SHIPPER'S STORAGE TANK.  DRIPPAGE WAS CAPTURED IN BUCKET , AND TREATED AND DISPOSED BY SHIPPER. THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO CARRIER TERMINAL FOR CLEANING AND EVALUATION AND REPAIR. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND KNOWN ENVIRONMENTAL OR OTHER PROPERTY DAMAGES.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: DRIVER TOOK EIGHT HOUR BREAK AT TRUCK STOP AND WHEN HE CHECKED TRAILER IN THE MORNING, HE DISCOVERED IT WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM A STEAM LINE ON BOTTOM OF TRAILER NEAR THE INTERNAL VALVE.  HE PLACED A BUCKET AND CALLED 911.  THE DUNN, NC FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AS WELL AS THE JOHNSTON COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM. CARRIER SENT TWO TRAINED TECHNICIAN LEVEL PERSONS FROM N. CHARLESTON, SC TO EFFECT TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM LEAKING TRAILER TO A DIFFERENT TRAILER.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON HAD TO BE CLEANED FROM THE PAVEMENT.  NO KNOWN ADDITIONAL PROPERTY DAMAGE, AND NO KNOWN ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE THE TRAILER THAT LEAKED WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND WILL BE TORN DOWN AND REPAIRED PRIOR TO REENTRY INTO COMMODITY HAULING.  MOST LIKELY FAILURE IS TRAILER FLOOR BREACH INTO THE STEAM HEATING PANELS.
PRODUCT WAS BEING PUMPED OFF OF CARGO TANK INTO STORAGE TANK. DURING THE PUMPING OPERATION, THE DELIVERY HOSE RUPTURED, RELEASING PRODUCT.
PRODUCT WAS BEING DELIVERED TO THE WRONG DESTINATION; THIS INCORRECT DESTINATION DID NOT HAVE ROOM FOR THE PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED AND AN OVER FILL SITUATION OCCURRED, RELEASING PRODUCT.

THE DRIVER WAS PULLING AWAY FROM THE GENERATOR'S SITE, 200 YARDS. HE HEARD A NOISE, STOPPED, AND OPENED THE DOORS TO DETERMINE THE PROBLEM.   A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS LEAKING.  THE DRIVER CALLED THE ETS HOME OFFICE LOCATED IN OKLAHOMA CITY, OKLAHOMA. ETS-OKS CONTACTED THE GENERATOR.  THE GENERATOR SENT A TEAM TO THE SITE, A MR. MIKE PONZIO. HE CALLED TO CONFIRM A SMALL AMOUNT, LESS THAN 2 GALLONS TOTAL.  THEY REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED LOOSE GRAVEL ALONG WITH THE TRAILER BACK TO THEIR LOCATION, OFF LOADED, AND CLEANED THE TRAILER.  THEY NOTIFIED LEPC/L.S. MCKAY. JOINT NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO TENNESSEE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT AND CONSERVATION COURTESY NOTIFICATION TO MR. CRABTREE OF THE DIVISION OF SOLID WASTE MANAGEMENT.  THE DRIVER INSTRUCTED AS TO PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING PROCEDURE.

AT 8:00 AM DRIVER WAS INSPECTING HIS LOAD AND NOTICED A DRUM LEAKING.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF TRACK AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND TRUCK WAS DECONTAMINATED.  ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS ALSO PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM. DRUM WAS THEN RELOADED ON TRUCK.  ALL DRUMS WE DELIVERED WITHOUT ANY FURTHER PROBLEMS.

AFTER REPORTING FOR DUTY AT 2130 CDT I WAS INFORMED THAT THE AIRCRAFT I WAS TO BE FLYING 4591B HAD A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF FORMALDEHYDE SPILLED IN ZONE 1 OF THE CARGO HOLD. UPON INSPECTION, THE FUMES WERE OVERPOWERING CAUSING ME TO FEEL NAUSEOUS AND MY EYES TO BURN.  BECAUSE OF THIS REACTION I DETERMINED THAT THE AIRCRAFT WAS NOT SAFE TO FLY.  OPERATION FOR THAT NIGHT WAS THEN SWAPPED TO 9623B. GREGORY G. HURLBURT

A TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN NASHVILLE, TN.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER WAS TO SEND SOMEONE TO REPAIR THE CAR ON 08/10 BUT DID NOT RESPOND.  ON 08/11 HAZMAT RECEIVED A REPORT THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHILE SITTING STILL.  PRODUCT WAS STREAMING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK AND DRIPPING ONTO THE BALLAST.  CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR AND THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE ARRIVED ABOUT THE SAME TIME.  THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR WAS RELIEVED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER FOUND THAT THE CAP ON THE 2 INCH LIQUID LOADING PIPE HAD STRIPPED THREADS AND WAS JUST SITTING ON TOP OF THE PIPE.  THE SHIPPER REPLACED THE DAMAGED CAP AND SECURED IT IN PLACE.  THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED ACID WITH SODA ASH AND WASHED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED.

ON AUGUST 6, 1997 AT APPROX 15: 30,  BURLINGTON MOTOR CARRIERS DRIVER WAS ADVISED THAT A SUBSTANCE WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOOR OF HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS AND NOTICED A 15 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM LYING ON ITS SIDE.  THE DRUM CONTAINED POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE AND HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE TOP.  WHEN THE DRUM WAS UPRIGHT THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CONTAINER LEAKED AN ESTIMATED 4 GALLONS INTO THE TRAILER, WITH ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND.  VERGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OUT OF LEMONT,IL WAS CONTRACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  VERGAN OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

column168: A PALLET (PAG8680BX) WAS SITTING ON THE LAX ROLLER SYSTEM WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THAT A BOTTOM FIBERBOARD BOX HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AND WAS LEAKING SOME FLUID ONTO THE ALUMINUM PALLET AND WETTING ADJACENT FIBERBOARD BOXES.  THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS PARTIALLY  UNLOADED AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS SPREAD OVER THE SPILLED LIQUID AFTER THE PUNCTURED BOX HAD BEEN PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE SIX PLASTIC BOTTLES, TWO OF WHICH SUFFERED THE PUNCTURE LEAKAGE, AND ONE OF WHICH WAS DENTED.  ONE OF THE ADJACENT BOXES HAD A SUFFIENTLY WETTED BOTTOM THAT IT WAS CUT OFF.  THE FREIGHT WITHIN WAS NOT HARMED. THE SALVAGE DRUM AND ITS CONTENTS WILL BE ATTENDED TO BY AN EPA AUTHORIZED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL COMPANY. THE TIME AND PLACE OF THE ACTUAL OCCURRENCE IS UNKNOWN.  THE ULD HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED FROM THE BAX ONTARIO STATION TO LAX.  REITERATED SAFETY INSTRUCTION IS DUE TO EMPHASIZE THE NECESSITY OF AVOIDING THIS SORT OF INCIDENT.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION RAIL FACILITY, TRAILER XTRX 632311 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT ONTO THE FLAT CAR UNDER IT. THE CONSIGNEE SENT A TEAM TO ASSESS THE SHIPMENT.  A VALVE IN ONE OF THREE 250 GALLON TOTE BINS WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ACCOUNT IT HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY INSTALLED.  THE VALVE WAS CORRECTLY POSITIONED AND PRODUCT NEUTRALIZED AN ESTIMATED 2 GALLONS OF CORROSIVE LIQUIDS NOS (SODIUM HYDROXIDE ) WAS RELEASED ; HOWEVER , MOST PRODUCT REMAINED IN THE TRAILER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: AFTER DERAMPING TRAILER TDSZ 540644 FROM FLAT CAR AT ITS DESTINATION RAIL FACILITY, PRODUCT WAS NOTICED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  BSNF AND CONSIGNEE'S CONTRACTOR ASSESSED THE SHIPMENT.  VOIDS WERE NOTED, AND SOME HAD BEEN FILLED WITH PALLERS. PALLET UNDERHANG WAS ALSO OBSERVED. A FAILED 15 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 13 GALLONS DUE TO MOVEMENT AND INTERACTION WITH ADJACENT PALLETS AND DRUMS.  PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED, AS WAS THE PAVEMENT AND FLAT CAR IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA

RUPTURE DISC FAILED WHEN TANK CAR ASTX5035 WAS COUPLED TO A CUT OF CARS. PRODUCT SPRAYED ONTO TWO ADJACENT CARS AND TO THE GROUND. SEVERAL TRACKS AND LEAD WERE REMOVED FROM SERVICE. THE SHIPPER SENT A RESPONSE TEAM TO REPLACE THE 135 PSI RUPTURE DISC AND TO DECONTAMINATED SPILLED SULFURIC ACID ALL WORK WAS COMPLETED BY 2015, AND SWITCHING OPERATIONS RESUMED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Incompatible Product
column168: FRONIA POLICE DEPARTMENT REPORTED AMMONIA SMELL COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 96593, A LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED CAR AND DETERMINED THAT LEAKAGE WAS FROM SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS ONLY 138 PSI, SO FOCUS OF REPAIRS WENT TO REPLACING DEFECTIVE 'O' RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. AS A PRECAUTION, THE CAR WAS SWITCHED TO A FACILITY NEAR BOVINA. A TANK TRUCK WAS USED TO OFF LOAD 1 1/2 TRUCK LOADS OF PRODUCT PRIOR TO THE SHIPPER'S ARRIVAL WITH REPLACEMENT 'O' RINGS. REPAIRS WERE COMPLETE AT 0700. THE SHIPPER REPORTED THIS PROBLEM ('O' RING MATERIAL COMPATIBILITY) IS BEING EVALUATED BY THE TANK CAR MANUFACTURER/MAINTAINER. INBOUND TRAIN: LNMX0151-06A

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: TANK CAR TGPX 3308, A LPG LOAD, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT. AN ASSESSMENT OF THE CAR REVEALED PRODUCT TO BE ESCAPING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE CAR WAS SWITCHED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING. FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT OVERLOADED, BUT HAD A DEFECT IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE OPERATION. AFTER UNLOADING, THE CAR WAS SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR CORRECTION OF THE MALFUNCTION. ESTIMATE THAT LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF LIQUID PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. TRAIN: R-ARZ0091-09A

A PASSING TRAIN REPORTED A STRONG SMELL FROM TANK CAR UTLX 48494, A LOAD OF  METHYL TERT BUTYL ETHER. ALL TRAIN TRAFFIC WAS SUSPENDED. BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE LOAD AND FOUND PRODUCT VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE. PRESSURE WAS VENTED. DISASSEMBLY OF THE VALVE REVEALED A DETERIORATED AND TORN GASKET. TEMPORARY REPAIRS WERE TO BLANK THE DEVICE. UPON RECEIPT OF A REPLACEMENT PART, IT WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION. FOUR TRAINS WERE HELD DURING THE ASSESSMENT, AND ARE INCLUDED IN ITEM 23(E). TRAIN: M-WELBEL3-14A

DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION, TRAILER RDWZ234645 WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED PRODUCT ONTO DECK OF FLAT CAR IN TRAIN Q-WSPNBY9-19A. column168: DRIVER NOT FAMILIAR WITH 10" DOME INSIDE 20" DOME. DID NOT FOLLOW PROCEDURE. DOME SEAL LEAKED. A CHECK LIST FOR DRIVERS TO FOLLOW IS TO BE IMPLEMENTED ASAP.

CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE DISCONNECTED HOSE FROM RECEIVING LINE BEFORE THE DRIVER WAS READY. MOST MATERIAL WAS CAUGHT IN CONTAINERS. 1-3  GALLONS WAS ABSORBED AND PACKED IN CONTAINER. DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON DELIVERY PROCEDURES, CONSIGNEE WAS INVOLVED IN REVIEW OR PROPER PRACTICES UNLOADING.

DRIVER HAD JUST STARTED TO OFF-LOAD THE CARGO TANK WITH AIR PRESSURE AND HAD OPENED HIS UNLOADING VALVE FOR ONLY APPROX. 5 MINUTES WHEN HE NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK. HE SHUT DOWN HIS UNLOADING LINE AND GOT THE SUPERVISOR, WHO CHECKED HIS TANK AND SAID IT WAS FULL. ABOUT 150 GALLONS CAME OUT INTO THE CONCRETE DIKE AROUND THE STORAGE TANK. THE CONSIGNEE PUT LIME ON THE SPILL AND INFORMED THE DRIVER THEY WOULD CLEAN UP AND DISPOSE OF IT AND TAKE THE REMAINING PRODUCT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK, GATX 30150, AUGUST 6, 1997, ALBANY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 6, 1997, A CONRAIL CREW DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 30150 CONTAINING POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HOURS, AUGUST 6, 1997, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER OF FIELD SERVICES AND GENERAL CAR FOREMAN ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND UPON EXAMINING THE CAR THEY DETERMINED THAT IT HAD RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER OF FIELD SERVICES WHO REPLACED THE DISK AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED AREA. AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, AUGUST 6, 1997, TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

(B) AACT JACKSON TERMINAL RECEIVED THIS SHIPMENT WITH ONE 55 GALLON DRUM TURNED ON ITS SIDE DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING AND BLOCKING ON INBOUND UNIT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT TO DESTINATION FOR DELIVERY.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HCL WITH AIR PRESSURE WHEN CARGO TANK WENT EMPTY. AIR PRESSURE GOES THROUGH UNLOADING LINE INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE STORAGE TANK AND IT CAUSES THE STORAGE TO BUBBLE UP AND THIS CAUSED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT THE TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK. A MR. WILLIAM STILLMAN AT THE CONSIGNEE TOLD OUR DRIVER NOT TO WORRY; HE WOULD CLEAN IT UP.

WHILE MOVING DRUMS EMPLOYEE NOTICED SMELL AND REALIZED THAT DRUM WAS LEAKING, EMPLOYEE LAID DRUM OVER TO STOP LEAK. THE SPILL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP BY ABSORBENT MATERIAL, DRUM WAS REPAIRED AND SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: EMPTY IBC'S HAD BEEN LOADED BACK IN WORTH TRUCK BY CUSTOMER. SOMEONE NOTICED LIQUID RUNNING OUT THE BACK OF THE TRUCK WHILE DRIVER MOVING THE TRUCK ACROSS THE PARKING LOT AND UP HILL TOWARD EXIT. ONE OF THE IBC'S WAS OBVIOUSLY NOT EMPTY, THE VALVE HANDLE WAS IN THE CRACKED OPEN POSITION AND THE COP WAS NOT TIGHTLY SECURED, SO AS DRUM CROSSED BROKEN PAVEMENT TOTE PROBABLY SLIDE IN THE TRAILER. NOT SURE IF VALVE VIBRATED OPEN, SLID INTO THE WALL AND OPENED, OR WAS OPENED WHEN FORK LIFT DRIVER LOADED AGAINST WALL. APPROX 5 GALLONS WAS LEFT IN THE EMPTY IBC AND APPROX 4 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE PARKING LOT. ABSORBENT AND SODA ASH WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE ACID. WE WILL INVESTIGATE FURTHER.

column62: Overfilled; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: DRIVER HAD LOADED AND DROVE TO IN-PLANT SCALE. UNIT WAS OVERWEIGHT SO SHIPPER SENT HIM BACK TO LOAD AREA TO UNLOAD THE EXCESS. DRIVER CONNECTED TANK TRAILER AS DIRECTED, AND HOOKED AIR PRESSURE TO TRAILER AIR INLET TO OFF LOAD SOME OF THE PRODUCT. AFTER 20 MINUTES, DRIVER SHUT DOWN SYSTEM AND CHECKED TRAILER. IT HAD GAINED 3 TO 4 ADDITIONAL INCHES OF PRODUCT. DRIVER INFORMED ATTENDANT AND CHECK WAS MADE, BUT DRIVER TOLD TO RECONNECT AND CONTINUE PROCESS. ONE HOUR LATER, PRODUCT WAS EMITTING FROM THE TRAILER PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE. PRODUCT WAS CAUGHT IN SHIPPER'S CONTAINMENT SYSTEM. SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE PLANT "HEAD" PRESSURE WAS GREATER THAN THAT BEING INTRODUCED INTO TRAILER AND THE PLANT "HEAD" PRESSURE OVERCAME. TRAILER RELIEF DEVICE. PROBLEM WAS SOLVED BY TRANSFERRING EXCESS PRODUCT INTO A DIFFERENT TANK TRAILER THAT ARRIVED TO LOAD THE SAME PRODUCT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. NO PRODUCT WENT ONTO SOIL, NOR WATERWAYS.

PAIL WAS PLACED AND SHRINK WRAPPED ON A PALLET BY THE SHIPPER, SHIPMENT WAS TRANSFERRED TO TRAILER NUMBER 615-4084 AT THE ULA FACILITY ON 8/28/97. A 500 LB PALLET FROM SHIPMENT NUMBER 151-808204 WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE PALLET FOR TRANSPORT TO SAN DIEGO. WHILE THE TRAILER WAS IN ROUTE TO THE USD FACILITY, THE WEIGHT OF THE HEAVY SKID CAUSED THE FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL TO BUCKLE AND SPILL THE CONTENTS OVER THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT AND ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. RECOMMEND THAT THE ULA FACILITY UTILIZE LOAD RACKS AND CHECK THE WEIGHT OF SHIPMENTS THAT ARE TO BE USED FOR TOP FREIGHT TO PREVENT THIS  TYPE OF INCIDENT FROM OCCURING IN THE FUTURE.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE PULLING INTO SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY DOWN HILL, A 16 GALLON DRUM TIPPED OVER SPILLING MATERIAL INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.

RECEIVED SHIPMENT FROM PARIS, FRANCE ON AUGUST 22, 1997. THE BOX WAS MISLABELED WITH IMPROPER SHIPPING NAME. WE RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE CONSIGNEE STATING THAT THE BOXES AND THE DOCUMENTATION WERE INCORRECT.

OIL WAS BEING PUMPED ONTO TUGBOAT WHEN APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS WERE ON BOARD THE CAPTAIN SAID TO STOP.  HE HAD NOT DIRECTED THE PRODUCT TO THE PROPER TANKS AND AN OVERFLOW OCCURRED.  THE COMPANY OWNING THE TUGBOAT CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  (ARUNDEL CORP, HAVRE DE GRACE, MD)

WHILE INSPECTING CARGO AR CONSIGNEE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A SMALL CRACK AT THE TOP ROLLER CHIME.  DRUM WAS DENTED IN THIS AREA  AND IT WAS FELT THE CRACK DEVELOPED WHILE IN TRANSIT.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO STEEL CONTAINMENT PAN.  A SLIGHT AMOUNT (LESS THAN 1 GALLON) OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED OUT REAR OF TRAILER ON TO ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THIS WAS PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENTS.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR DECONTAMINATED.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

"DRIVER, IAN HAWKINS, ENTERED THE BRANCH ON A SAT MORNING AROUND 10 AM.  THERE WAS NO SUPERVISORS ON DUTY AT THAT TIME.  IAN SAID HE WALKED BY SUPPLY ROOM AND SLIPPED IN SOME LIQUID THAT WAS ON THE FLOOR.  HE OPENED THE DOOR AND SAID HE SAW A 55 GALLON DRUM TIPPED OVER AND LEAKING.  HE CLAIMED THAT THERE WAS A RADIOACTIVE PLACARD ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  HE CALLED POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WHEN THEY INVESTIGATED THE SCENE, THEY FIGURED OUT THAT IT WAS ONLY ANTI FREEZE." STATEMENT FROM DAVID CONFORTI - OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR - BUF

column168: (A - B) A SYNCOR VEHICLE WAS RETURNING FROM DELIVERING CONTAINERS TO SEVERAL HOSPITALS.  THE CONTAINERS ARE USED TO DELIVER UNIT DOSES OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL USED IN MEDICAL IMAGING.  IT APPEARS THAT THE DRIVER DRIFTED INTO THE CENTER OF THE HIGHWAY HITTING A CRASH CUSHION TO A RAILROAD OVERPASS.  AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT ONE STEER AMMO CAN WAS EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE.  THE STEEL AMMO CAN OPENED ON IMPACT WITH THE GROUND. A UNIT DOSE CONTAINER WAS FOUND SEPARATED FROM THE STEEL AMMO CAN. THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE UNIT DOSE CONTAINER WITH NO RELEASE OF MATERIAL.  NINE OF THE CONTAINERS TRANSPORTED WERE "RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL."  ONE CONTAINER WAS LABELED "RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, NOS" THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE REMAINED UNTIL AUGUST 12, 1997. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  THE RESPONSE INCLUDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM.  THE ROAD WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS.

CAUGHT ON FIRE, CAUSING DAMAGE TO SURROUNDING CYLINDERS.  THE CAUSE WAS UNDETERMINED.  WE FOLLOWED OUR EVACUATION PLAN:  EVACUATED OUR EMPLOYEES OUT OF THE BUILDING, CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, ACTIVATED DELUGE SYSTEM AND FIRE ALARMS. column168: TRAILER #53-2335 WAS ON ITS WAY INTO BATH ON SUNDAY MORNING.  THE DRIVER WAS FLAGGED DOWN BY A PASSING CAR TELLING THEM THEY WERE LEAKING SOMETHING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER STOPPED AND CALLED DISPATCH.  THE DRUM OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS PUNCTURED BY ANOTHER SHIPMENT OF STEEL.  THE ASST BREAK MANAGER WENT OUT TO THE SCENE.  HE CALLED THE FIRE DEPT THEY RESPONDED WITH THE LEHIGH COUNTY HAZ MAT RESPONSE UNIT AND OTHER RESPONSE TEAMS.  THE DRUM WAS PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM SUPPLIED BY THE RESPONSE TEAM.  THE TRAILER HAD A NEUTRALIZING COMPOUND PLACED ON THE SPILL AND THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE BATH TERMINAL  BY AUTHORITY OF THE FIRE DEPT.

column168: DURING THE MORNING SORT, THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING, BAKING SODA WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILLED MATERIAL TO NEUTRALIZED IT.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER WHO FAXED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THAT DOCUMENT INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS NOT REGULATED.  AS WE HAD INVESTIGATED A SIMILAR CASE IN 1995, AND THAT THIS MSDS WAS EIGHT YEARS OLD, I WAS SUSPICIOUS.  I CALLED THE MANUFACTURER ON THE MSDS.  IN FACT, THERE WAS A NEW MSDS, THIS ONE CLEARLY INDICATED THE MATERIAL TO BE UN1791.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER A SECOND TIME AND ADVISED THAT THIS SHIPMENT WAS REGULATED AND THAT I WOULD BE REQUIRED TO NOTIFY THE FAA.  I DID CALL THE FAA IN NEWARK, NJ I ADVISED THAT WE WOULD HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING N FAA INSPECTION NEXT WEEK.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column168: DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  UPON OPENING THIS BOX WE FOUND THREE AEROSOL CANS AND A ONE-PINT CAN OF WHAT APPEARS TO PAINT. THE AEROSOL CANS WERE AN ACTIVATOR FOR THE PAINT.  WE BELIEVE THE PAINT TO BE FLAMMABLE AS IT REQUIRED AN ACTIVATOR.  I HAVE NOR HAD ANY EXPERIENCE WITH A LATEX PAINT REQUIRED AN ACTIVATOR. WHILE THERE WERE CAN CLIPS ON THE FRICTION LID OF THE PAINT, ONE CAME DISLODGED, ALLOWING THE PAINT TO ESCAPE.  IN ADDITION, THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION ARROWS DISPLAYED ON THE BOX.  THERE WERE NO LABELING, MARKINGS , SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER, CHERYL WILLIAMSON AS WELL AS MARK MCBRIDE, THE PRESIDENT OF INSULTHERM.  MARK INDICATED THAT THIS WAS A PERSONAL SHIPMENT AND THAT IT WAS A MISTAKE.  I ADVISED THAT THE FAA WOULD BE NOTIFIED.  I SPOKE TO FAA SPECIAL AGENT MARK FITZPATRICK WITH MIAMI FAA CASFO THIS MORNING.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column168: CSX RAILROAD WAS MOVING A EMPTY RAIL CAR ADJACENT TO PROPERTY.  AT RAIL SWITCH BLUE FLAG DIRECTION WAS POINTING TO HY YIELD RAIL SPUR, CONDUCTOR DID NOT NOTE THE DIRECTION AND MOVED THE EMPTY RAILCAR HY YIELD PROPERTY WHERE CHLOROPICRIN AND METHYL BROMIDE ARE UNLOADED.  EMPTY RAILCAR HIT AND DERAILED CONNECTED CHLOROPICRIN RAILCAR. NO CHEMICAL RELEASE FROM THE RAILCAR.  ONE POUND RELEASE FROM UNLOADING HOSE CONNECTION WHICH WAS PURGED EMPTY AT THE TIME.  A ADJACENT METHYL BROMIDE RAILCAR WAS BUMPED BUT NOT DERAILED.  THERE WAS NO REPORTED SPILLAGE FROM EITHER RAILCAR.  NO DAMAGE TO VALVES, MODERATE DAMAGE TO BRAKE ASSEMBLY AND FRAME.

AS DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF DIESES FUEL, A CAP VIBRATED LOOSE CAUSING APPROXIMATELY. 20 GALLONS OF FUEL TO SPILL ONTO GROUND.  DRIVER SHUT OFF ALL VALVES & TURNED PUMP OFF. column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: UPON RECEIVING A TELEPHONE CALL FROM A SECURITY GUARD AT A NEARBY INDUSTRIAL FACILITY, THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO HAVE DISCHARGED MATERIAL ON THE GROUND. DISCHARGE WAS DUE TO A REACTION IN THE TANK TRAILER, THUS CREATING HEAT AND EXCESS PRESSURE.  THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE RELIEVED THE EXCESS PRESSURE. CONTAINMENT OF THE AREA WAS STARTED IMMEDIATELY.  MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO BE ON THE TRAILER AND ON THE GRAVEL OF THE PARKING LOT. CLEAN-UP WAS DONE BY WASTE MANAGEMENT FIELD SERVICES CONTRACTOR. CLEAN-UP WAS DONE BY REMOVING SOIL AND DIRT FROM THE PARKING LOT AND PLACED INTO A ROLL-OFF BIN FOR DISPOSAL.  MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM TRAILER AND ALSO PLACED INTO ROLL-OFF BIN. PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS TESTED AND FOUND TO BE IN PROPER WORKING ORDER, WITH VALVE OPENING AT THE PROPER DESIGN PRESSURE.  PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON CARGO TANK TRAILER FUNCTIONED AS DESIGNED, THUS PREVENTING A MORE SERIOUS INCIDENT.
DRUM ARRIVED AT DAYTON LEAKING, THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY AN ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND THE DRUM WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION.

THE CONTENTS OF 3 55 GALLON DRUMS ESCAPED FROM THE CLOSURES AS A RESULT OF EXPANSION DUE TO ELEVATED TEMPERATURE DURING TRANSIT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A TRANSPORT LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID FROM THE LOADING STATION IN THE MINE AREA UP TO THE NORTHWEST STORAGE TANK.  WHILE ENROUTE, HE TOOK A CORNER TOO FAST, CAUSING A ROLL OVER OF THE TRUCK AND TRAILER UNIT.  THE TRAILER ROLLED ONTO MINE PROPERTY THROUGH THE GUARD FENCE, THE PRESSURE/VACUUM VALVE PIPING BROKE AT THE TANK AND ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF THE ACID INTO THE LEACHING AREA. THIS IS WHERE THE ACID IS PIPED INTO FROM THE STORAGE TANK.  IT WAS DECIDED TO DRAIN THE TANK OUT ONTO THE PAD. THE AREA WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER AND DITCHED INTO THE LEACHING AREA.  THERE WAS BERM BUILT WITH A FRONT-END LOADER TO PROTECT THE AREA FROM THE ROADWAY UNTIL THE FENCE WAS REPLACED THE NEXT DAY.  THE SPEED LIMIT HAS BEEN REDUCED TO 40 MPH.

PERSONNEL AT THE FACILITY CLEANED UP SPILL AND DISPOSED OF MATERIAL AND DEBRIS.  TRANSFORMER WAS OFFLOADED AT FACILITY.  NO MATERIAL ENTERED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.

column168: DURING SWITCHING CAR REPORTED LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION BY BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDERS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE WASH-OUT. THE WASH-OUT WAS CORRODED AND ONE BOLT WAS MISSING. THE VAPOR PRESSURE WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK SLOWING THE LEAK TO APPROXIMATELY ONE DROP PER MINUTE. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE, WHICH IS LESS THAN 5 MILES FROM THE BNSF YARD, WHERE THE CAR WAS UNLOADED.

DURING SWITCHING, TANK CAR UTLX 646249 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION BY BNSF HAZMAT RESPONDERS, THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED. THE SHIPPER'S INSPECTION OF THE CAR DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE TO BE THE "O" RING GASKET OF THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE HAD FAILED CAUSING VAPOR AND LIQUID TO PASS BY IT. THE SHIPPER STATED THAT THIS IS A CHRONIC PROBLEM WITH THEIR COMMODITY AND UTLX TANK CARS. THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED AND A PLUG WAS INSERTED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DURING SWITCHING, TANK CAR UCLX 30030 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION BY BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDERS, THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE CAUSED BY A LOOSE BLIND FLANGE ON THE LIQUID EDUCATION. SEVERAL OF THE FLANGE'S SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND ONE WAS MISSING. THE VERY CORRODED BOLT WAS LATER FOUND ON THE DECK OF THE TANK CAR. THE RESPONDERS RESECURED THE BLIND FLANGE, NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AND RELEASED THAT TANK CAR.

column14: 17 MI. NE OF RANKIN, TX OFF HW
column168: DRIVER WAS PUMPING LOAD OFF WHEN UNLOADING HOSE SEVERED FROM THE TRANSPORT PUMP DISCHARGE PIPING ALLOWING CRUDE OIL TO BE RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND. DRIVER TERMINATED PUMPING OPERATION, SECURED SITE, AND REPLACE HOSE. REVIEWED IMPORTANCE OF PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE/INSPECTION OF HOSES AND HOSE CONNECTIONS WITH DRIVERS. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BIOREMEDIATED ON SITE.
TANKER #450 SPILLED PRODUCT ONTO ASPHALT IN FRONT OF THE DOCK AREA. THE DRIVER SPILLED THE MATERIAL WHEN DISCONNECTING THE HOSE FROM THE STORAGE TANK.

FOUND ONE CARTON LEAKING WHEN RECEIVED AT DOCK, UPON INVESTIGATING ONE CAP WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE ON ONE OF THE METAL CONTAINERS IN ONE OF THE BOXES-CLEANED UP A MINOR (8-12 OZ.) AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE WITH SODA SORB AND STAGED THE DAMAGED CARTON IN ATLANTA TERMINAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BAG - SENT THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT ON. MY RECOMMENDATION TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE IS TO MAKE THE PACKAGING MORE STURDY.

DRIVER MADE IMPROPER CONNECTIONS WITH THE HOSES, AND HAD THE SUCTION HOSE AND DISCHARGE HOSE REVERSED. THIS CAUSED MATERIAL TO BE PUMPED FROM THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK INTO THE TANK TRUCK THROUGH THE NORMAL DISCHARGE LINES. THE TANK TRUCK OVERFLOWED FROM ITS OPEN DOME. PRODUCT ENTERED STORM DRAIN, WHICH FLOWS INTO THE SCHUYLKILL RIVER. THE N.R.C. WAS CALLED, AS WELL AS THE PENNSYLVANIA D.E.P., AND THE CITY OF PHILADELPHIA FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CITY WATER DEPARTMENT RESPONDED. CARRIER SENT REPRESENTATIVES AND HIRED AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO REMEDIATE THE SITE. THERE WERE NO KNOWN INJURIES.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER STOPPED FOR RAILROAD CROSSING AND WHEN HE STARTED TO MOVE TRUCK AGAIN HE HEARD A PRESSURE RELEASE AND SAW FUME RELEASE (WHITE VAPOR). SOME LIQUID PRODUCT HAD SPILLED INTO CRASH BOX AND GOTTEN INTO OVERFLOW TUBES. A PASSING MOTORIST INHALED SOME OF THE FUMES AND HAD TO BE TREATED AT SISTERSVILLE GENERAL HOSPITAL AT SISTERSVILLE, WV. HIS NAME IS VIRGIL MC MULLEN. HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. THERE WERE NO OTHER KNOWN INJURIES. CARRIER SENT A TRAINED TECHNICIAN TO EVALUATE TRAILER AND PERFORM CLEANUP. TRAILER HAD BEEN REFURBISHED DURING JULY AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE WRONG MATERIAL WAS USED FOR THE "RUPTURE DISC". A METALLIC DISC WAS USED, INSTEAD OF THE RECOMMENDED CERAMIC TYPE-METALS ARE CORRODED AND WEAKENED BY THIS PRODUCT.

SMALL AMOUNT OF MOISTURE WAS NOTICED BENEATH DRUM UPON ARRIVAL AT TSDF. REVIEW OF MANIFEST AND REVIEW OF DRUMS IDENTIFIED LEAKING DRUM AS "SATIN HYDROXIDE SOLUTIONS". SOURCE OF LEAK WAS BUNG ON TOP OF DRUM THAT HAD BEEN OVER TIGHTENED. THIS CAUSED BUNG TO SKIP A GROOVE AND TO LEAVE A SMALL CRACK FOR LIQUID TO SEEP THROUGH. TRAILER HAD METAL FLOOR AND NO LIQUID WAS RELEASED TO ENVIRONMENT. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT AND BROOMS AND BUNG WAS LOOSENED AND RETIGHTENED. TRAINING RE: OVER TIGHTENING OF BUNGS ON POLY DRUMS WILL BE GIVEN TO FIELD PERSONNEL TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE IMPACT CAUSED ONE OF THE INNER CONTAINER LIDS TO POP, SPILLING IT'S CONTENTS. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT PADS AND THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAITING DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR MISJUDGED A TURN AND STRUCK THIS PIECE AS IT SAT IN A DESIGNATED STAGING AREA, CAUSING SOME OF ITS CONTENTS TO SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT PADS AND THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAITING DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION.

column168: PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON STORAGE TANK FAILED, CAUSING RELEASE OF PRODUCT.

FRONT FORK OF HI-LO PUNCTURED DRUM WHILE DOCKMAN ATTEMPTED TO GET UNDER SKID. DOCKMAN IMMEDIATELY RETRIEVED ABSORBANT AND NOTIFIED DOCK SUPERVISOR. ABSORBENT WAS PLACED AROUND TRAILER TO CONTAINER HAZMAT. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND A MSDS SHEET WAS OBTAINED. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND CAME OUT TO SPILL LOCATION TO CLEANUP HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: UPON OPENING THE DOORS TO THE 1 PM DIAMOND J LOAD FROM EL MONTE, CA. STEPHEN WHEELER DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE PAINT HAD BEEN SQUISHED AND CREATED A PINHOLE LEAK IN THE CONTAINER. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF WASTE PAINT HAD LEAKED INTO THE TRAILER. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED AND THE WASTE PAINT WAS CLEANED UP WITH CLAY ABSORBENT. THE EL MONTE, CA BRANCH WILL BE NOTIFIED.

WHILE LUKE WILKINSON WAS UNLOADING THE 10AM MASON/HEATH LOAD, HE DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM THAT HAD "PRESSURED" UP, WITH THE TOP OF THE LID PROTRUDING OUT. HE CAREFULLY PICKED IT UP WITH THE PARROT BECKS AND BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER. WHILE EXITING FROM THE TRAILER, THE DRIVE TIRES ON THE FORKLIFT BUMPED UP ON THE DOCK PLATE, JARRING THE DRUM SLIGHTLY, CAUSING THE DRUM TO FALL STRAIGHT DOWN 6 INCHES AND SPLASHING THE LIQUID OUT OF THE CONTAINER. THE MATERIAL THAT SPLASHED OUT WAS COVERED WITH CLAY ABSORBENT AND CLEANED UP.
DRIVER OVERFILLED TRAILER DUE TO FAULTY GAUGE. DRIVER INSTRUCTED TO MONITOR TRAILER AND NOT TO RELY ON GAUGES FOR LOADING. DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO NOT OVER-FILL TRAILERS.
PRODUCT WAS RELEASED WHILE DISCONNECTING HOSE FROM HEADER PIPE BECAUSE OF FAULTY CHECK VALVE. DISCUSSED WITH DRIVER ABOUT CLOSING PLUG VALVE PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING HOSE. REPAIRED CHECK VALVE.

TANK CAR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MONTGOMERY, AL, REPORTED TO SLASH FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER  RESPONDED A TEAM TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM. SHIPPER TEAM REPLACED A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK AND RELEASED THE CAR.

A CSXT SWITCHER WORKING CUSTOMERS IN PLANT CITY, FL, MADE A SHOVING MOVE INTO ONE INDUSTRY BUT THE SWITCH WAS LINED OUT HY YIELD BROMINE. THE SWITCHED SHOVED A CUT OF CARS INTO HY YIELD, COUPLED TO A METHYL BROMIDE CAR (UTLX 920230) AND SHOVED IT INTO A CHLOROPIERIN CAR (PLMX 27508) THAT WAS CONNECTED FOR UNLOADING. THE PLMX 27508 WAS SHOVED OFF THE END OF THE TRACK AND DERAILED UPRIGHT. THE UNLOADING HOSES WERE TORN LOOSE WHEN THE CAR MOVED AND A RESIDUE OF PRODUCT THAT REMAINED IN THE HOSE (LESS THAN 1 PINT) WAS SPILLED ON THE GROUND. THE LOCAL F.D. WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. HY YIELD PERSONNEL CONDUCTED THE PRODUCT CLEANUP. THE PLMX 27508 WAS RE RAILED AND FINISHED THE UNLOADING.

A TANK CAR IN TRAIN Q46113 WAS OBSERVED TO BE SMOKING FROM THE TOP. CAR WAS SET OUT ON SIDING AT CAMAK, GA. LOCAL RESPONSE AGENCIES NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED CSXT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CORRECT THE LEAK. CONTRACTOR FOUND THE BALL VALVE ON THE AIR LINE WAS OPEN AND VAPORS WERE ESCAPING FROM AROUND THE VALVE OPERATING STEM. THEY CLOSED THE VALVE AND THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: TANK CAR LOAD CARBON DIOXIDE NOTED VENTING IN SIDING AT CAVE CITY, KY. SHIPPER NOTIFIED.
TANK CAR LOAD ETHYLENE GLYCOL NOTED LEAKING BOTTOM OF TANK CAR NEAR "A" END. CONTAINER PLACED WHERE TANK CAR. SHIPPER RESPONSE TEAM TRANSFERRED LOAD TO TANK TRUDS. TANK CAR MOVED TO SHOP.
TANK CAR LOAD CARBON DIOXIDE NOTED VENTING IN RAIL YARD. TANK CAR ISOLATED. SHIPPER RESPONSE TEAM INSPECTED TANK CAR WHICH HAD STOPPED VENTING. TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

TANK CAR REPORTED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MONTGOMERY, AL. CAR ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. SHIPPER SENT RESCAR TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM. RESCAR RESPONDED ON 8/21; THEY FOUND THE CAR HAD A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK. RESCAR REPLACED THE DICK. THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

THE TRAIN CREW OBSERVED VAPORS COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR. UTLX 130122. THE UNDERSIGNED WAS INFORMED ALONG WITH THE OPR. CTR. THE UNDERSIGNED RESPONDED AND FOUND THE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID FILL LINE WAS NOT SEVERE. THE UNDERSIGNED RESPONDED BY SECURING THE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID FILL LINE. ALL OF THE VALVES AN FITTINGS WERE EVALUATED.

TANK  CAR FOUND WITH A SLASH  LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN CHARLESTON, SC. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER SENT RESCAR TO REPAIR THE CAR. RESCAR REPLACE A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

A TANK CAR OF CARBON DIOXIDE WAS REPORTED TO BE VENTING VAPORS WHILE SETTING ON A SIDING AT JEFFERSONVILLE, IN. CAR WAS VENTING FROM THE LOW PRESSURE VENT HAD BEEN VENTING FOR SEVERAL HOURS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO INSPECT THE CAR AND BLEED OFF ANY EXCESS PRESSURE AS NECESSARY.

WHILE MAKING OUTBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, A CARMAN DETECTED A CHEMICAL ODOR. HE DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS ORIGINATING FROM TANK CAR GATX 67354. THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED. THE CAR WAS THEN CUTOUT OF THE TRAIN ALONG WITH 8 OTHER CARS. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE SUBJECT CAR. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND THAT 3 OF THE 8 MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND 1" AIRLINE CONNECTION WAS OPEN. BOTH CONDITIONS WERE CORRECTED AND NO FURTHER EVIDENCE OF VAPR LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED.

YARD CREW OBSERVED VAPORS COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX 1239. THE CAR WAS THEN ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED. THE SHIPPER SENT PERSONNEL FROM RESCAR INC. TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR. THE REPAIR CREW FOUND THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING, THUS ALLOWING HOL ACID VAPORS TO ESCAPE. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED. THE CAR WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

CARMAN OBSERVED LIQUID SLOSH OUT OF TOP GLNX 3542 WHEN IT WAS COUPLED. CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR DID NOT FIND A DEFINITE SOURCE OF THE LEAK, BUT SUSPECTED THAT THE MANWAY CLOSURE BOLTS WERE NOT TIGHTENED EVENLY. THE CONTRACTOR RETIGHTENED THE BOLTS WITH EVEN TORQUE. ALL FITTINGS AND CLOSURES WERE THEN CHECKED WITH A PHOTO IONIZATION DETECTOR. NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

THE TOTES WILL BE LOADED DIFFERENTLY IN THE FUTURE.

WE FLIPPED THE 55 GALLON DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO AVOID SPILLING ANYMORE. IN THE FUTURE WE NEED TO BE CAREFUL WITH LOADING DRUMS WITH FORKLIFT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ZIMMER PATIENT CARE LOCATED AT 714 KADERLY AVE., NEW PHILADELPHIA, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THIS TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT 200 WEST OHIO AVENUE, DOVER, OH TO PICK UP A SHIPMENT FROM ANOTHER GENERATOR.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOOR TO THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER NOTICED A LEAKING CONTAINER AND A PUDDLE ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PLACED SORBENT MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE VEHICLE TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND PREVENT AN ESCAPE  TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR AND A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE.  UPON THE CREW'S ARRIVAL,  A CLEANUP WAS INITIATED.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND CLEANUP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO A SUITABLE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS ALSO PLACED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS OF MATERIAL WERE SHIPPED TO THE DESTINATION FACILITY NOTED ON THE ORIGINAL HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST.  AN INSPECTION OF THE INCIDENT REVEALED THE CAUSE OF THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER TO BE A LOOSE PIECE OF UNSECURED EQUIPMENT.  A FLEXIBLE BUNGY CORD WAS EMPLOYED TO SECURE THE DRUM CART TO THE WALL OF THE VEHICLE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  THIS BUNGY CORD BROKE AND ALLOWED THE DRUM CART TO SLIDE FREE.  THE DRUM CART SLID INTO A DRUM, CONSEQUENTLY PUNCTURING THE WALL OF THE CONTAINER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE DRIVER SECURED THE DRUM CART TO THE WALL OF THE VEHICLE.  AT THE TIME, THERE WAS NO INDICATION THAT THE BUNGY CORD WOULD FAIL.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO CAREFULLY INSPECT ANY AND ALL SECUREMENT DEVICES UTILIZED.

ALL LEAKING FREIGHT WAS REMOVED AND WAS PUT IN OVERPACKS FOR REMOVAL.  IT WAS GENERATED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE YOUNG'S SECURED AREA AND DRIVER CONTINUED ON.

DURING THE INSPECTION OF THE TANK TRAILER, ONE OF THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL TURNED A VALVE ON THE TANK TRUCK AND ABOUT ONE PINT OF PRODUCT ESCAPED BEFORE THE VALVE WAS PROPERLY CLOSED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  NONE OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

The injured person was a lease operator.  The product line stopped up when the air hit the sulphur and it hardened.  As the operator was trying the chip the product out of the valve, the product broke lose and hit the drivers arm.  He sustained burns from the product, was transported to the hospital, prescribed an ointment for the burn and released. He was off work until September 2, 1997.  He is back at work and has no further complications.

column168: ON 8/1/97 HAZMAT LEAD SORTER, RHONDA CLONCH REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE HAZMAT SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC. I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, MATT GROSVENOR RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THE SHIPMENT WA ISOLATED. TECHNICIAN GROSVENOR DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE. INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE TWO FIBERBOARD BOXES. THESE CONTAINED ONE GLASS RECEPTACLE EACH. THERE WAS ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED. THE CLOSURE WAS NOT PROPERLY PLACED ONTO THE GLASS RECEPTACLE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

OUR DRIVER, EUGENE GRAHAM, PICKED UP A SHIPMENT OF CYLINDERS ALONG WITH OTHER FREIGHT AND UPON RETURNING TO OUR TERMINAL YARD NOTICED  A HISSING SOUND. HE INSPECTED HIS VEHICLE AND REALIZED THAT THE NOISE WAS NOT COMING FROM HIS EQUIPMENT, BUT FROM THE SHIPMENT OF CYLINDERS THAT HE HAD PICKED UP. I CALLED THE SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER AND ALSO INFORMED OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR, JEFF TURNER. THE SHIPPER SENT OVER A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST, RICK TOLE, WHO ADVISED US TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO AIR OUT THE TRAILER. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED THE WHOLE BUILDING AND ALLOWED THE CYLINDER TO DEPLETE ITSELF INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THEY SAID THAT THEY COULD NOT CONTAIN THE VAPORS AND MOVED THE TRAILER TO THE BACK OF THE YARD. THEY ALSO WILL RETURN ON 8/3/97 WITH ASSISTANT SERVICE CENTER MANAGER, DAN HOLT, TO CHECK TRAILER FOR ANY FURTHER HAZARDOUS DANGER. THIS SERVICE CENTER COMPLIED WITH ALL SAFETY PROCEDURES AND REGULATIONS IN ISOLATING SPILL, EVACUATION, AND CONTACTING THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. NO ONE WAS INJURED AND CLEAN UP WAS MINIMAL.

column168: TO WHOM IT MAY CONCERN; ON AUGUST 18, 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00PM, OUR DRIVER LAGANT CROSBY DIED WHEN OUR GASOLINE FILLED TANKER & TRUCK OVERTURNED AND EXPLODED ON THE RAMP FROM THE BALTIMORE BELTWAY INTERSTATE 83.  OUR 1997 FORD TRACTOR & 1989 FRUEHAUF TRAILER PASSED A SAFETY INSPECTION BY THE D.O.T., 2 WEEKS AGO.  ALSO THE MD STATE POLICE OFFICER T. HARROLD, THE RECONSTRUCTION OFFICER STATED THAT OUR TRUCK & TRAILER PASSED A POST ACCIDENT SAFETY INSPECTION. WE ARE UNSURE AS TO HOW THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED.  WE ARE BEING LED TO BELIEVE THAT SPEED MAY HAVE BEEN A FACTOR.  WE ARE AWAITING THE OUTCOME FROM THE INVESTIGATION BY THE MD STATE POLICE AT THIS TIME. OUR COMPANY OFFICIALS WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  OWNERS NANCY & TERRY HARDESTY WENT TO THE ACCIDENT SITE IMMEDIATELY.  OUR SAFETY CONSULTANT, GLEN RUESCHLING WAS ALSO PRESENT AT THE SCENE.  MANAGERS PHIL WOOLFORD AND MARK PULLEN CAME TO THE SITE AROUND MIDNIGHT AND STAYED UNTIL THE BODY WAS EVACUATED. MARYLAND DEPT. OF THE ENVIRONMENT, ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, A &A SERVICES, STATE POLICE, BALTIMORE COUNTY FIRE DEPT.  AND NUMEROUS OTHER PRIVATE COMPANIES RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  WE HAVE (2) TWO MAJOR CONCERNS AT THIS TIME, FIRST IS FOR THE FAMILY.  WE ARE DEVASTATED BY OUR LOSS AND FOR THE LOSS OF LAGANT'S FAMILY. SECONDLY WE ARE VERY CONCERNED ABOUT THE OUTCOME OF THE INVESTIGATION. WE HAVE BEEN OVERWHELMED TO SAY THE LEAST BY ALL OF THIS.  WE HAVE LOST NOT ONLY AN EMPLOYEE BUT AVERY GOOD FRIEND.  WE ARE TRYING OUR BEST AT THIS TIME TO KEEP UP WITH EVERYBODY'S NEED FOR INFORMATION AT THIS TIME PLEASE CALL AND WE WILL TAKE CARE OF YOUR NEEDS AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. HARDESTY & SON TAKES SAFETY VERY SERIOUSLY.  WE ALSO WOULD LIKE TO THANK ALL THE PROFESSIONALS WHO WERE INVOLVED IN THIS ACCIDENT. OUR SINCERE GRATITUDE AND APPRECIATION FOR ALL OF YOUR IMMEDIATE RESPONSE WAS GREATLY APPRECIATED.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: ON AUGUST 12 1997 DRIVER STEVE WADE WAS PULLED INTO THE BOW-HILL SCALE ON I-5 SOUTH, FOR A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF A PLACARDED LOAD.  UPON INSPECTION OF THIS LOAD IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO  CARBOYS CONTAINING SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WERE LEAKING FROM THEIR VENT PLUGS.  THE APPROXIMATE QUANTITY WAS 3 TO 4 FLUID OUNCES, AND HAD NOT LEAKED ANY FURTHER THAT BUNG AREA.  AT THAT TIME, THE INSPECTING OFFICER, PUT THE TRUCK OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL SUCH TIME AS THE LEAKING VENT PLUGS COULD BE REPLACED. STEVE WADE THEN NOTIFIED ME BY PHONE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE  TO DISPATCH EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO CLEAN UP AND REPLACE THE LEAKING VENT PLUGS. THIS ACCOMPLISHED, THE DRIVER WAS ALLOWED BACK IN SERVICE TO COMPLETE HIS DELIVERY SCHEDULE.  UPON FURTHER ANALYSIS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VENT PLUGS HAD FAILED, AND WE HAVE SINCE SWITCHED TO A PLUG FROM A DIFFERENT MANUFACTURER.  FURTHER, EACH DRIVER IS NOW REQUIRED TO CARRY IN THEIR VEHICLE, THE NECESSARY TOOLS AND REPLACEMENT PARTS, AS WELL AS CLEAN-UP AND CONTAINMENT KITS, IN THE EVENT A VENT FAILS IN THE FUTURE.
CUSTOMER HAD IMPROPER AND ILLEGAL INSTALLATION NOT VISIBLE TO DRIVER.  TANK (275 GAL. CAP.)  RUPTURED IN BASEMENT.

JEFF BOTWINICK FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 58369. THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE FOR COASTAL CHEM, MR. JIM WIDRIG 307-771-5647 WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A NON-RELATED SHIPMENT TO IT'S CONSIGNEE. THE CARTON OF CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS ON THE TRAILER.  AN EMPLOYEE OF THE COMPANY BEING DELIVERED TOO, (CHARLES SCHUSTER) WAS OPERATING A MOTORIZED LIFT (MORE LIKE A MOTORIZED PALLET JACK AFFAIR ON WHICH HE RODE STEERING WITH THE HANDLE),  AS HE NEARED THE TRAILER, THERE WAS AN INCLINE ON THE CORROSIVE LIQUID SITTING ON THE TRAILER, WHEN THE CARTON CONTAINING THE FOUR- ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS STRUCK, THE CARTON AND THE FOUR JUGS BURST FROM THE FORCE GENERATED BY THE LIFT STRIKING THEM. CORROSIVE LIQUID (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) SPRAYED IN SEVERAL DIRECTIONS.  THE LIFT OPERATOR (SCHUSTER) GOT SOME OF IT IN HIS EYES.  HE WAS TREATED BY PARA-MEDICS WHO HAD RESPONDED WITH THE CRYSTAL LAKE FIRE DEPT.  THE FIRE DEPT.  PERSONNEL AIRED OUT THE FUMES FROM THE BUILDING AFTER TAKING ALL PERSONNEL OUT.  THE FIRE DEPT.  CLEANED UP THE SPILL, NEUTRALIZED THE ACID AND CLEANED ALL EQUIPMENT.  DAN GRISCHOW WITH THE CRYSTAL LAKE FIRE DEPT ADVISED THAT THE SPILL WAS APPROX 4 GALLONS. IT HAD BEEN CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  THE PARA-MEDICS HAD TREATED THE LIFT OPERATOR AT THE SCENE.  THE POWER TRUCK OPERATOR TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT HE HAD LOST CONTROL OF THE LIFT AS HE CAME DOWN THE SLIGHT INCLINE ON THE DOCK.  HE ADMITTED HE HAD NO CONTROL WHEN THE CARTON OF ACID WAS STRUCK

column168: UNDECLARED PACKAGE FOUND IN UPS FACILITY LEAKING.

"DRIVER PICKED UP 5 GALLON DRUM OF CORROSIVE LIQUID FROM EL DOROAD CHEMICAL.  HE PLACED THE DRUM IN BETWEEN PALLETS OF METAL COILS SO IT WOULD NOT MOVE AROUND DURING TRANSPORT. DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR DAMAGE HAS BEEN A WARNING LETTER FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW PROCEDURE." STATEMENT FOR LANA NEUKIRCH - OFFICE MANAGER SAT

OUR MAINTENANCE MAN REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE VALVE HANDLE.

WE HAD TO BRING MOST OF THE 140 SOLVENT BACK TO THE PLANT AND PUT IT INTO OUR STORAGE TANK.

MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY "RMCC" DENVER AT 1248 HOURS THAT JUNCTION CITY, KANSAS POLICE DEPARTMENT HAD CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER SERVICE CENTER ADVISING THAT TANK CAR "FLIX" 8035"  WAS LEAKING AND A TRAILER PARK HAD BEEN EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. MR. STINE ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1400 HOURS AND MET WITH FIRE CHIEF MIKE YOUNKIN AND AFTER SOME DISCUSSION WAS ALLOWED TO INSPECT CAR. FOUND THE VAPOR AT 85 PPM UPON OPENING THE HOUSING COVER PLATE WHICH DIMINISHED TO 20 PPM SHORTLY AFTER OPENING THE COVER. REMOVED THE COVER FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE AND FOUND THE VAPOR ESCAPING FROM AROUND THE SLIP TUBE. PRESSURE ON THE TANK WAS 80 PSI. STINE WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING NUT 1/4TH TURN WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. NOTIFIED MR. DUANE DAVIS WHO INDICATED CAR WOULD BE REPAIRED PRIOR TO LOADING AT ENID OKLAHOMA. TRAFFIC HAD BEEN REROUTED FROM WASHINGTON AND GRANT THRU THE 1100 BLOCK GRANT. CRITIQUE OF THE INCIDENT WAS HELD AUGUST 19, 1997.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED LOADED TANKCAR ACFX 86538, AND OBSERVED PRODUCT ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED, THAT WHOEVER SECURED THE CAR INADVERTANTLY LEFT A BUNGI CORD HANGING ON THE RIM OF THE MANWAY. THEY THEN POSITIONED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE ON TOP OF THE METAL HOOK OF THE BUNGI CORD WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK AND EVENTUALLY BREAK THE GASKET. MANAGER RODABOUGH REMOVED THE BUNGI COR AND THE BROKEN GASKET. HE INSTALLED A TEMPORARY, GORTEX GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. TANK CAR WAS ALSO MISSING THE RIGHT SIDE A-END PLACARD, WHICH WAS REPLACED BY MGR. RODABOUGH. CHEMTREC, MR. CRISS YOUNG, TOOK THE REPORT AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 59215. THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE FOR ELF TOCHEM NORTH AMERICA, MR. BOB TYCE, GIVEN THE INFORMATION CONCERNING REPAIRS AND STATED THEY WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY STEVE BERKI, DIRECTOR, CENTRAL REGION, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, REPORTING A DERAILMENT AT BARSTOW, CALIFORNIA, WITH A UP AND BNSF TRAIN. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO BARSTOW AND LOCATED TANK CAR GATX 43917 RESTING ON IT'S LEFT SIDE AT A 90 DEGREE ANGLE. BNSF MECHANICAL FORCES HAD MADE ENTRY INTO THE DERAILMENT AND OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE PACKING GLAND AT THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AT A RATE OF 4 TO 5 DRIPS PER MINUTE. (B) DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY STEVE BERKI, DIRECTOR, CENTRAL REGION, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, REPORTING A DERAILMENT AT BARSTOW, CALIFORNIA, WITH A UP AND BNSF TRAIN. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO BARSTOW AND LOCATED TANK CAR UTLX 75646 RESTING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE AT A 90 DEGREE ANGLE. BNSF MECHANICAL FORCES HAD MADE ENTRY INTO THE DERAILMENT AND OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE CLOSURE AT THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. A CONTINUAL DRIP WAS NOTED FROM AROUND THE AREA BETWEEN THE CAR NOZZLE AND THE COVER PLATE BELOW THE #4 SECUREMENT BOLT. THE COVER PLATE WAS A STANDARD 8 BOLT CLOSURE. DUE TO THE DAMAGE TO THE TANK CAR, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS TO HIGHWAY VEHICLES FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE OUR DELIVERY TRUCK WAS PARKED ON OUR PROPERTY, DURING TEMPORARY STORAGE, AMMONIA BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE CARGO TANK AT THE CAPACITY (PERCENT) GAUGE.  THE CAPACITY GAUGE FAILED INTERNALLY  WHICH ALLOWED AMMONIA TO ESCAPE. ABOUT 100 GALLONS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK AND VAPORIZED. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND MANAGED THE INCIDENT. TWENTY PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES FOR ABOUT 45 MINUTES, AND THEN ALLOWED THEM TO RETURN HOME.  THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED. RESPONSE 400641.  ONE PERSON WAS HOSPITALIZED FOR OBSERVATION, FOUND OK AND RELEASED TO GO HOME THE NEXT MORNING. INCIDENT PREVENTION WE ARE UNABLE TO DETERMINE WHY THE CAPACITY GAUGE FAILED.  WE WILL EMPHASIZE THAT OUR INSPECTION PROGRAM INCLUDE A CAREFUL INSPECTION OF THE CAPACITY GAUGE AND RELATED COMPONENTS.

column168: NASHVILLE, TENN. DRIVER GARY DUPUIS LOADED A SKID OF DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT, WHEN THE BLADES BROKE THROUGH THE PALLET AND PUNCTURED ONE (1) DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 25-30 GALLONS LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM AND PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED IN THE HAZMAT BAY.  THE INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH THE DRIVER, GARY DUPUIS.

IT APPEARS THE WHEELCHAIR WAS LOADED IN THE AIRCRAFT WITHOUT REMOVING THE BATTERY. THE WHEELCHAIR WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE ON ARRIVAL IN LAX. IT MAY HAVE BEEN LOADED ON ITS SIDE* OR IT MAY HAVE TIPPED IN FLIGHT. IT WAS NOT TIED DOWN IN THE BELLY. A SMALL AMOUNT OF FLUID LEAKED ONTO TWO (2) CREW BAGS AND ONE PASSENGER'S BAG. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE AIRCRAFT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WITH A BAKING SODA AND WATER SOLUTION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON AUGUST 16, 1997 AMERICAN WEST AIRLINES (AWXA) FLT. #1158 ARRIVED AT MILWAUKEE, WISCONSIN AIRPORT (MKE) AT APPROXIMATELY 1545 HOURS FROM PHOENIX, ARIZONA (PHX). DURING THE COURSE OF UNLOADING THE BAGGAGE, TWO (2) APPROVED CONTAINERS HOLDING ONE (1) EACH BATTERY, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC, STORAGE WERE DISCOVERED IN THE AFT BIN OF THE B-737-300. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT BOTH BOXES WERE PROPERLY MARKED AND THE BATTERIES WERE PACKAGED IN AN APPROVED POLYETHYLENE BAG CONTAINING TWO (2) SUPER SORB PADS FOR EACH BATTERY, ALL OF WHICH WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A CORRUGATED CARDBOARD BOX WHICH HAD BEEN APPROVED FOR USE BY CONTINENTAL AIRLINES (CALA) Y THE FAA. HOWEVER, CLOSE EXAMINATION OF ONE (1) OF THE BOXES, WHICH HAD BEEN FOUND IN AN UNSECURED CONDITION, TITLED AGAINST THE SIDES OF THE BIN DISCLOSED THAT THE ACID FROM TWO (2) OF THE SIX (6) CELLS HAD APPARENTLY LEAKED THROUGH THE POLYETHYLENE BAGS INTO AND THROUGH THE OUTSIDE (BOX) CONTAINER AND FROM THERE TO THE DECK OF THE AIRCRAFT. AWXA OPERATIONS AND MAINTENANCE WERE CONTACTED. NO REPORT WAS MADE TO (#2052)(DEPARTING 2 HOURS AND 39 MINUTES LATE.) FACTORS CONTRIBUTING TO THE SPILL INCLUDED FAILURE TO USE THE COMPANY APPROVED NON SPILLABLE VENT CAPS AND TO SECURE THE BOXES CONTAINING THE BATTERIES IN THE AIRCRAFT AS MANDATED IN THE AWXA CUSTOMER SERVICE MANUAL. NO INJURIES, LOSS OF LIFE NOR DAMAGE TO THE AIRCRAFT WAS SUSTAINED. CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN INCLUDED PERSONAL AND VOICE MAIL BRIEFING OF ALL CONCERNED PERSONNEL, INITIATING A CAMPAIGN TO USE ONLY THE APPROVED REPLACEMENT PLASTIC BOXES FOR THE SHIPMENT OF WET BATTERIES AND IMPLEMENTING PROCEDURES TO INSURE THE TIMELY NOTIFICATION OF ALL CONCERNED REGULATORY AGENCIES.

ON 08/13/97 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, SPILL TECHNICIAN, TAMMY FLORENCE RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL SHE DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR. THE OUTER BOX WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZMAT CERTIFICATIONS DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNER PACKAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THIS FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED (ACETONE) A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. THERE WERE 11 X 4 OUNCES OF ACETONE OF WHICH ONE BOTTLE LEAKE ITS CONTENTS. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL WITH THIS SHIPMENT. THE FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED OTHER NON-REGULATED MISCELLANEOUS PRODUCTS. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS CLOSURE FAILURE. THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column168: DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO INDICATED THAT THIS WAS NOT A FLAMMABLE LIQUID AS IT WAS A GROUND SHIPMENT. I EXPLAINED THAT FEDEX DOES NOR OFFER A GROUND SERVICE AND THAT EVERYTHING TENDERED TO US HAD TO BE PREPARED AS THOUGH IT WERE GOING TO FLY.  BASED ON MY CONVERSATION WITH THE SHIPPER I FELT I HAD ENOUGH INFO TO NOTIFY THE FAA THAT WE HAD AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 8-26-97, MYO FRED SAMUELSON ADVISED CTS MGT LERCH THAT TANK CAR KCCX 3063 WAS LEAKING. ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE 2 INCH LIQUID LINE AT THE RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON PER HOUR. A PLASTIC BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO COLLECT THE PRODUCT. INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED THAT THE 2 INCH LIQUID LINE CAP PLUG WAS LOOSE AND INTERNAL PRESSURE OF TANK WAS FORCING PRODUCT OUT OF LIQUID LINE. AFTER VENTING THE CAR AND TIGHTENING THE LIQUID LINE CAP PLUG 2-1/2 TURNS, THE LEAK STOPPED. MGR LERCH HAD CAR SET OUT AT THE SPEER HOUSE TRACK FOR INSPECTION THE FOLLOWING MORNING. ON 8-27-97, IN THE COMPANY OF FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR, FRED BRYANT, THE CAR WAS INSPECTED AND GAUGED. IT WAS THEN NEUTRALIZED WITH A WATER/SODIUM BICARBONATE SOLUTION AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT. WHILE INTERVIEWING THE TRAIN CREW, IT WAS LEARNED THAT THEY HAD NOTICED THE CAR LEAKING WHILE INSPECTING THEIR TRAIN AND HAD NOTIFIED MYO SAMEULSON. A CHECK OF WAYBILL AND CONSIST INFORMATION SHOWED THE CAR WAS A LOAD WITHIN A CUT OF EMPTY TANK CARS RETURNING TO KENNECOTT COPPER FOR RELOADING. AT 1035 HRS, MGR LERCH SPOKE TO MNTCE SUPV. ENGLEHARD CORP, RALPH KEEN. HE INDICATED THE CAR HAD BEEN RELEASED IN ERROR TO THE I.C.R.R. WITH A CUT OF EMPTY CARS RETURNING TO KENNECOTT COPPER. WHEN QUESTIONED ABOUT THE INSECURE CONDITION OF THE CAR, HE ADVISED THAT THEY HAD NOT ATTEMPTED TO OFF LOAD THE CAR PRIOR TO ITS BEING ACCIDENTALLY RELEASED. HE NOTED THAT ONCE THE CAR WAS DISCOVERED MISSING, UNION PACIFIC CUSTOMER SERVICE CENTER HAD BEEN CONTACTED AND BILLING CHANGED TO ROUTE THE CAR BACK TO ENGLEHARD CORP. AT 1440 HRS., MGR LERCH CONTACTED GREG GEERHART, MGR OF TRANSP.., KENNECOTT COPPER, REGARDING THE INSECURE CONDITION OF THE CAR. HE ADVISED THAT LOADING RECORDS INDICATED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN PROPERLY SECURED PRIOR TO BEING RELEASED. NOTIFICATIONS:2122 HRS, 8-27-97, CHEMTREC, BOB WIBLE, #59276; 2112 HRS., WYOMING DEQ, SGT STOWERS.

THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP GASKET WAS ALSO IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT. RISK-CAR RESPONDED BY REQUEST OF THE QUAKER OATS SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, BILL MYERS IN CEDAR RAPIDS. GATX 40064 HAD BEEN IN THE SHOP FOR REPAIR WORK THE PREVIOUS WEEK PER MR. MEYERS. WHEN MGR. WILDER ARRIVED THERE WERE 4 FIREFIGHTERS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY SET UP A SPILL POOL UNDER THE TANK CAR. FROM THE MELROSE FIRE DEPT. IC WAS CAPT. CONAWAW WHO HAD ALREADY NOTIFIED THE STATE EPA. STATE EPA REPRESENTATIVE, EDWARD OSOWSKI WAS ALREADY ON THE SCENE. BOLTS WERE SECURED AND GASKET REPLACED. EPA REQUESTED THAT THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR BE DECONTAMINATE AND THE SOIL UNDER THE TANK CAR BE CLEANED UP. HERITAGE WAS CALLED AND PERFORMED THE DECONTAMINATION AND SOIL REMEDIATION.

DRIVER ARRIVED FUEL FARM AND HOOKED HOSES TO CUSTOMERS PUMP. THE ATTENDANT SET THE VALVES AND WE STARTED UNLOADING.  PART WAY THRU FIRST COMPARTMENT THE OVERFLOW ALARM WENT OFF.  DRIVER WAS GOING TO SHUT THE UNLOADING VALVE OFF, AND THE ATTENDANT, JIM A VANYS HR.  FROM CORPORATE AIR SAID THE ALARM MUST HAVE MALFUNCTIONED BECAUSE HE HAD ROOM IN THE TANK FOR 18,000 GALLONS, SO THEY, LET IT KEEP PUMPING FOR 4/5 MINUTES.  IT STARTED TO OVERFLOW AT REAR OF TANK, BUT NOT MUCH GOT OUT BECAUSE DRIVER WAS WATCHING TANK AND BY THE VALVE AND SHUT IT OFF IMMEDIATELY AND HE SHUT PUMP OFF.  HE SWITCHED TANKS AND FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT FURTHER TROUBLE. DRIVER CALLED BUT WAS UNABLE  TO REACH SO HE LEFT A WITHOUT FURTHER TROUBLE.  DRIVER CALLED BUT WAS UNABLE TO REACH SO HE LEFT A MESSAGE ON ANSWERING MACHINE BEING THAT THE SPILL WAS SMALL AND CONTAINED IN THEIR DIKE AND POSING NO EMERGENCY, DRIVER WENT ON WITH THE REST OF MY WORK.

UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND AN ODOR ABOARD THE AIRCRAFT AFTER USING A GAS MEASURING DEVICE TO MEASURE ANY POSSIBLE FLAMMABLES AND FINDING OUT WHAT APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT NEEDED WE BEGAN OUR INVESTIGATION. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS WE FOUND 1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLE OF PAINT WITH NO MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE THIS SHIPMENT WAS A FLAMMABLE PAINT SHIPMENT WHICH LEAKED 1/2 GALLON. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED WITH PAPER AS A CUSHIONING MATERIAL. THE ABOVE SHIPMENT LEAKED DUE TO CLOSURE FAILURE. THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY AT THE ILN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY.

column168: ON 8/26/97 I WAS CALLED VIA RADIO BY DAY SORT SUPERVISOR JOEL BOTTS THAT HE HAD A PACKAGE AT DOOR B-2 OF OUR SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT THE ABOVE ABX AIR, INC. ADDRESS, THAT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND FURTHER NOTED A SLIGHT ODOR OF A TYPE OF CLEANER.  I INSPECTED THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE AND DID NOT SEE ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS THAT WOULD INDICATE THAT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MAY BE INSIDE.  I OPENED THE PACKAGE TO INSPECT THE INNER CONTENTS AND DISCOVERED 14 VARIOUS TYPES AD QUANTITIES OF AEROSOLS.  SEE ATTACHED LISTS FOR TYPES AND QUANTITIES.  DUE TO OTHER LEAKING SHIPMENTS THAT NEEDED INVESTIGATED AND TIME FACTORS, I BAGGED THIS SHIPMENT AND OVERPACKED IT INTO AN 85 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM, THEN HAD IT PLACED INTO OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON 8/22/97, SPILL TECHNICIAN, MATT GROSVENOR WAS DISPATCHED TO BLDG "A" OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT THE ABOVE ADDRESS.  THE CALL DESCRIBED A PACKAGE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID AND IT WAS EMITTING A STRONG ALCOHOL TYPE ODOR.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS EVACUATED OF 4 EMPLOYEES, BUT DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR EXPANDING 11 MORE EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION.  UPON ARRIVAL, MR.  GROSVENOR FOUND THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION, BUT DID NOT SEE ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS THAT WOULD IDENTIFY THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE FOR A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS, MR. GROSVENOR FOUND 3 X 4 OZ GLASS BOTTLES BROKEN OUT OF AN 8 COUNT.  THE GLASS BOTTLES WERE WRAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP, BUT THERE WASN'T ANY TYPE OF ABSORBENT USED, THE MANUFACTURES LABEL STATE THAT THE CONTENTS (FLEXIBLE COLLODION) WOUND CLEANSER WAS EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE  AT THAT POINT MR. GROSVENOR PUT THE SHIPMENT IN A PLASTIC BAG AND PLACED IT IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY, UNTIL IT COULD BE INVESTIGATED BY THE FAA.  UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA THE SHIPMENT WILL BE EITHER FORWARDED OR RETURNED PER THE SHIPPERS REQUEST.  THE SHIPMENT WILL BE TRANSPORTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AND IN COMPLIANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS ACCORDING TO TITLE 49CFR.

ON OPERATIONS DATE 8/19/97, AT 23:06 SPILL TEAM MEMBERS SHELLY MORGAN AND MATT GROSVENOR RESPONDED TO A SPILL THAT WAS REPORTED LEAKING AND HAVING AN ODOR IN BUILDING "B" AT DOOR B-26 AT THE "ERI" SORT AREA LOCATED AT OUR ADDRESS ABOVE.  AT THAT TIME IT WAS REPORTED THAT 20 EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN EVACUATED OUT OF THE IMMEDIATE AREA DUE TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL, P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN SHELLY MORGAN DONNED A CARTRIDGE MASK AND APPROACHED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT AND NOT SEEING ANY HAZARDOUS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE SHE OPENED IT TO SEE WHAT WAS LEAKING.  INSIDE SHE DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER GLASS ONE LITER RECEPTACLES CONTAINED "BENZOYL CHLORIDE" SHE THEN RADIOED THIS TO HAZ MAT SUPERVISOR, KAREN SCHATZMANN WHO RESEARCHED IT IN THE  C.H.R.I.S MANUAL FOR CHEMICAL SPILLS AND FOUND THAT, SELF BREATHING APPARATUS AND FULLY ENCAPSULATED CHEMICAL SUIT WAS REQUIRED IF THIS MATERIAL SPILLED.  TECHNICIAN MORGAN THEN EGRESSED AND DRESSED OUT IN THE REQUIRED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE GEAR. TECHNICIAN MORAN APPROACHED THE PACKAGE AGAIN AND NOTED THAT THE PACKAGE APPEARED TO BE A NON-SPECIFICATION PACKAGE.  INSIDE SHE FOUND 1 X 1 LITER (2.5KG) THAT THE PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURE HAD CRACKED RELEASING THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL. THERE WASN'T ANY ABSORBENT MATERIAL SALVAGE DRUM, TAKEN TOT HE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY AND PLACED IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL IT COULD BE INVESTIGATED BY THE FAA.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/RELEASE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BELIEVED TO HAVE TRANSITED THROUGH THE INPUT AREA WHERE THE DAMAGE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS A 90 LEAD PIG THAT CONTAINED THREE METAL BOLTS WITH A CAPSULE OF THE SOURCE CAESIUM-137 SEALED INSIDE OF EACH.  THE PIG ALSO HAD A COMBINATION LOCK THAT WAS TO HOLD THE RECESSED FRICTION LID OF THE CONTAINER IN PLACE.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THIS LOCK WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY AND CAME OFF THE PIG IN HANDLING.  THIS ALLOWED THE THREE SOURCES BOLTS IN THE PIG TO COME OUT. SOMEHOW THE CONTAINER WAS RESEALED WITHOUT THE SOURCE BOLTS IN THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER CONTINUED ITS TRIP THROUGH THE OUTBOUND SORT WAS LOADED ONTO ITS DESTINATION FLIGHT GREENSBORO, NORTH CAROLINA.  THE RECIPIENT UPON RECEIVING THE PACKAGE IMMEDIATELY RECOGNIZED THAT THE SOURCES WERE NOT IN THE CONTAINER AND CALLED FEDEX AND A SEARCH WAS INITIATED IN THE MEMPHIS HUB FOR THE SOURCES. THE SOURCES WERE LOCATED IN THE MEMPHIS HUB SORT FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM CST ON 8/29/97 REPRESENTATIVES FROM TRU TEC FLEW INTO MEMPHIS BY CHARTERED AIRCRAFT LATER THAT NIGHT TO RETRIEVE THE SOURCES FOUR MEMPHIS FEDEX EMPLOYEES PAUL PATRICK, OPHRA PHILLIPS, BONITA BRICE & KATRINA FITZPATRICK DID HANDLE THE SOURCES AND RECEIVED EXPOSURE AT MINIMUM LEVELS.

HERMAN LEWIS WAS THE DOCKWORKER WHO REPORTED THE PROBLEM TO HIS SUPERVISOR (TIM STRUEBING) THE PROBLEM WAS THAT PRO #830425411 SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF A STACK RACK WITHOUT ANY DUNNAGE OR SUPPORT AROUND IT. HERMAN LEWIS WAS UNLOADING A TALL SKID NOT KNOWING THAT A HAZMAT DRUM WAS LOADED ON TOP OF A STACK RACK IN FRONT OF THE TALL SKID. WHILE PULLING THE TALL SKID OUT THE DRUM (PAIL) FELL OFF THE STACK RACK. DRUM WAS DAMAGED (FERGUSON - HARBOUR WAS CALLED FOR CLEAN UP.

CARRIER TRANSPORTING A LOADED VAN TRAILER TO CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED OF A CARGO PROBLEM BY PASSING MOTORIST.  DRIVER STOPPED UNIT AND PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE PRODUCT DRIP AT THE TRAILER DOORS.  A RESPONSE/CLEAN-UP COMPANY (FERGUSON HARBOR) WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED BY THE CARRIER.  FERGUSON HARBOR ENTERED THE TRAILER AND IDENTIFIED 1 STEEL 55 GALLON DRUM WITH A BOTTOM SEAM WELD FAILURE.  THE DRUM WAS SUPPLIED FILLED AND LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER BY THE SHIPPER. FERGUSON HARBOR CAUGHT IN THE TRAILER CONTAINMENT SYSTEM AS WELL AS THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM THE TRAILER.  ALL RESPONSE ACTIVITIES WERE OVERSEEN BY THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE AND THE LOCAL FIRE AUTHORITY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DRUM FAILURE.  AFTER CLEANUP ACTIVITIES, THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT INCIDENT. NOTE:  COPY OF UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NUMBER AR911447 COVERING THIS SHIPMENT IS ATTACHED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Passenger Mark Sanders checked a package containing a gasoline powered scooter.  During transit, the gasoline leaked from the tank and saturated the outer fiberboard carton.  A small amount of gasoline also appeared on the cargo compartment flooring.  The spill was cleaned and the package was sent to an outside contractor for proper packaging and documentation.  At the time of acceptance, the presence of the scooter was not ascertainable to the passenger service representative.  The normal security steps were taken to insure the passenger knew who packaged the box and that it had been in his possession at all times.  This packaged traveled as baggage and did not have any labels or markings indicating the presence of a dangerous good.

column168: During the unloading process, a small pool of a black liquid was found on the cargo compartment floor.  Upon further inspection of a shipment consigned as "household goods," a container of liquid drain cleaner was found.  The shipment was not declared as a dangerous good, thus did not have proper markings, labels or documentation. The spill was cleaned and the aircraft was returned to service.
